title: Elderly Commission organises pre-retirement workshop (with photo)
content_text:
p>
The following is issued on behalf of the Elderly Commission: The Elderly Commission (EC) and the Health, Welfare and Food Bureau today 
(September 30) co-organised a pre-retirement workshop at the Hong Kong 
Convention and Exhibition Centre. At the workshop, eight representatives coming 
from the business sector, the Government and non-governmental organisations 
(NGOs) shared with more than 100 participants their views on issues to be aware 
of after retirement and their experience in planning for retirement. Four

of after retirement and their experience in planning for retirement. Four 
retirees and soon to be retirees had also shared their opinion on retirement and 
retirement planning. Speaking at the workshop, the EC Chairman, Dr Leong Che-hung, said the EC hoped 
enterprises could through this workshop realise the need to make pre-retirement 
preparation for their staff and assist them to adapt to retirement 
psychologically and socially. He said the workshop provided a good opportunity for enterprises, the Government 
and NGOs to get together to explore the roles of different parties, study ways

and NGOs to get together to explore the roles of different parties, study ways 
to foster a caring culture, and to better utilise the rich experience and 
knowledge of retired employees. The Permanent Secretary for Health, Welfare and Food (Health and Welfare), Ms 
Sandra Lee, said everyone should plan for each stage of his/her own life, with 
no exception to retirement. She also said most soon to be retirees in Hong Kong 
were psychologically and physically fit, after retirement they could spend more 
time participating in social activities, developing hobbies, learning new things

time participating in social activities, developing hobbies, learning new things 
and with their families. In short, they entered into a new chapter of life - 
Active Ageing.  General Manager and Head of Retirement Benefits of HSBC Insurance (Asia-Pacific) 
Holdings Ltd, Ms Luzia Hung, shared the findings of a global survey commissioned 
by the group on retirement. Group Human Resources Manager of CLP Holdings Ltd, 
Mr KT Lai, and Head of Human Resources of the Hong Kong Jockey Club, Mrs Anna

Lo, also briefed the participants their pre-retirement activities for the staff. Other speakers in the workshop were Assistant Director of Social Welfare, Mrs 
Kathy Ng; Assistant Director of Health, Dr Chan Wai-man; and Clinical 
Psychologist of the Department of Health, Miss Zion Law, who suggested ways to 
live an active retirement life. Senior Manager of the Hong Kong Society for the 
Aged, Ms Leung Yin-yin, and Manager of St James Settlement, Mr Daniel Doo,

introduced supporting services for retirement preparation. Ends/Saturday, September 30, 2006
Issued at HKT 14:47
